4:38:28 PM [express] POST /api/queries/analyze 200 in 7343ms :: {"id":2,"queryText":"my university does not provides good hyginic water","language":"en","aiCategory":"🎓 Education Rights (Student Health & Safety)","aiExplanation":"Universities normally have a legal and policy duty to provide a safe learning environment, which includes access to clean and hygienic drinking water. If the water is unsafe or unhygienic, you can raise a formal complaint within the university and, if necessary, with external authorities responsible for public health or higher education oversight.","aiSteps":["Document the problem: Take clear photos/videos of the water quality, collect dates/times when the issue occurs, and keep any medical reports if you or others became sick after consuming the water.","Check university rules and policies: Look at your student handbook, hostel regulations, or website for policies on health, sanitation, hostel facilities, and complaint procedures so you can reference them in your complaint.","File a written complaint inside the university: Send an email or written application to the relevant office (e.g., hostel warden, dean of students, facilities/maintenance, or student welfare office), clearly describing the problem, attaching evidence, and requesting immediate action to provide safe drinking water.","Escalate through formal grievance channels: If nothing changes, escalate to higher authorities such as the Registrar, Vice-Chancellor, or the university’s grievance redressal committee, and ask for a written response and timeline for fixing the issue.","Contact external bodies if necessary: If the university still does not act and the water is unsafe, contact your local public health department, consumer protection/higher education regulatory body, or ombudsman, and submit a complaint with all your documented evidence."],"createdAt":"2026-03-10T16:38:21.246Z"}
